{
  "texts": [
    "It is rational to rely on the heuristic when there is a correlation between the criterion and recognition (Gigerenzer & Goldstein, 1996).",
    "This suggests that 'activating' the availability heuristic need not be manipulative, even though it means to bypass rationality in the sense of bypassing conscious deliberation.",
    "In summary, the bypassing rationality criterion suffers from over-and under-inclusivity.",
    "Since it also lacks the advantage of being relatively simple-insofar as bypassing rationality is more difficult to operationalise than hidden influence-it is of questionable relevance for the aim to design for non-manipulation.",
    "The hidden influence and bypassing conceptions fail because manipulation is a varied and diverse phenomenon."
  ]
}